'''Jane Jebb Mansbridge''' (born November 19, 1939) is an American [[political scientist]]. She is the Charles F. Adams [[Professor]] of Political Leadership and Democratic Values in the [[Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]].

Mansbridge has made contributions to [[democracy|democratic]] theory, [[feminist]] scholarship, and the empirical study of social movements and [[direct democracy]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Williams | first = Melissa S. | title = Beyond the empirical-normative divide: the democratic theory of Jane Mansbridge | journal = P.S.:  Political Theory and Politics | volume = 45 | issue = 4 | pages = 797–805 | publisher = Cambridge Journals | doi = 10.1017/S1049096512001035 | date = October 2012 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1017/S1049096512001035 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last = Rouyer | first = Muriel | title = Jane Mansbridge | journal = Raisons Politiques| volume = 40 | issue = 4 | pages = 135–156 | publisher = Presses de Sciences Po | doi = 10.3917/rai.040.0135 | date = November 2011 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.3917/rai.040.0135 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref>

In April 2018, Mansbridge was announced to be the 24th laureate of the [[Johan Skytte Prize in Political Science]].

==Early life and education==
Mansbridge received her B.A. from [[Wellesley College]] in 1961, her M.A. in [[history]] from [[Harvard]] in 1966, and her Ph.D. in government from [[Harvard]] in 1971.

==Career==
Mansbridge previously taught at the [[University of Chicago]] and [[Northwestern University]].

Mansbridge is particularly known for the distinction between unitary and adversary democracy (based on common and conflicting interests respectively), and for her concepts of gyroscopic representation (based on inner motivation), the selection model of representation, and surrogate representation (representation of others outside one's district).<ref>{{cite web|last=Dovi|first=Suzanne|title=Political Representation|url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/political-representation/|publisher=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|accessdate=17 April 2014|date=17 October 2011}}</ref> She is currently working on the necessity for legitimate coercion created by our need for "free use" (or "free access") goods.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Mansbridge | first = Jane | title = What is political science for? | journal = [[Perspectives on Politics]] | volume = 12 | issue = 1 | pages = 8–17 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press|Cambridge Journals]] on behalf of the [[American Political Science Association]] | doi = 10.1017/S153759271300368X | date = March 2014 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1017/S153759271300368X | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref>

==Prizes, awards and honors==
*1971&ndash;1972: National Science Foundation Postdoctoral Fellow.
*1982&ndash;1983: [[Rockefeller Foundation]] Humanities Fellow.
*1985&ndash;1986: [[Institute for Advanced Study]], Member.
* 1987: Co-recipient, APSA Kammerer Award. 
* 1988: Co-recipient, APSA Schuck Award. 
*1991&ndash;1992: [[Russell Sage Foundation]], Visiting Scholar.
*1994: Elected member, [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]].
*1997&ndash;1998, 2001&ndash;2002: [[Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences]], Fellow. 
*1998: Jane Mansbridge Scholar-Activist Award created, Northwestern University. 
* 2004: Radcliffe Graduate Society Medal.
*2005: Jane Mansbridge Research Paper Award (annual) created, Women and Public Policy Program, Kennedy School, [[Harvard University]].
*2004&ndash;2005: [[Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study]], Fellow 2004&ndash;2005.
* 2010: Midwest Women's Caucus for Political Science Outstanding Professional Achievement Award.
* 2011: APSA James Madison Award.
*2012&ndash;2013: [[American Political Science Association]] President.
*2014: elected a [[British Academy#Fellowship|Corresponding Fellow of the British Academy]].<ref name="BA Fellow">{{cite web | url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/british-academy-announces-42-new-fellows/2014585.article | title=British Academy announces 42 new fellows | publisher=Times Higher Education | date=18 July 2014 | accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>
*2017: Received a ''honoris causa'' doctorate by the French university Sciences Po. The ceremony took place December 12.

